Wow! If I could give 6 stars, I would. The ambience, the service, the food, wine...it was all amazing! I had 5 courses (boyfriend had 3 and we shared the cheese and dessert courses) Each course was just perfect. Course 1: lobster salad, seared scallops. Courses 2 & 3: coconut Thai curry with seafood, roast Maine lobster, bison, and herb crusted tuna. Course 4 was the cheese course. There was a wide variety of cheeses to choose from and our server was very knowledgeable. For dessert we had a pear tart. The portions were the size I expected and wanted, more than a tasting but less than a meal. We also had the sommelier do wine parings with each course, including chees and dessert. AMAZING! They also brought out a small plate of sweets and gave us a small cake to take home. I had it the next day, so good! If you are in San Fran you have to eat here. The whole experience was perfect and it was a lot less expensive that I thought it would be. (a little over $200pp with gratuity and that included the wine pairings!)

Gary Danko's cuisine = ambrosial Ambrosial def. 1. exceptionally pleasing to taste or smell; especially delicious or fragrant 2. worthy of the gods; divine My eyes were most certainly larger than my stomach and I had a difficult time deciding what to get. On the left side of the menu, there is a seasonal tasting menu available. On the right side, you can customize a 3, 4 or 5 (or probably more if you wanted) course menu. The categories to choose from included appetizers, fish & seafood , meat & poultry, cheese course and dessert. You could select as many items from each category as you like for your 3 ($66), 4 ($83), or 5 ($98) (or more) courses. At first glance I wanted one salad, one fish, one game and 2 desserts. I wanted the passion fruit chiboust and the trio of creme brulees. My husband scolded me for wanting two desserts. Talk about not watching what I am eating! Then, the table next to us received their duck dish and lobster dish. And then the cheeses being served to the table on the other side of us looked so good, too!! I was already planning on getting the lamb and the lobster, but the duck looked SO good!! So, at this point, I was trying to mentally prepare myself to pig out on a 7-course meal. Then, reality set in. I can't eat that much even if I wanted to. Time to reign it in and be realistic here. In the end we had one 4-course and one 5-course (we ordered the cheese course to share). Our selections: Salad / Soup - a) Thai Lobster Salad with Melons, Pickled Cucumbers and Mango Dressing b) Risotto with Lobster, Laughing Bird Shrimp, Corn, Butternut Squash, Parmigiano-Reggiano and Basil Oil The husband proclaimed the risotto the best he has ever eaten. The texture of the risotto was incredible. I've definitely never had a risotto quite like that. It was fabulous. Fish & Seafood - a) Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelles, Corn and Tarragon b) Branzini with Orzo, Roasted Peppers, Patty Pan Squash, Tomato Confit and Watercress The texture of the branzini - light and crunchy on the outside, so moist, light and flaky on the inside ... The lobster was delicious and the corn was so sweet. Meat & Poultry- a) Herb Crusted Loin of Lamb with Tian of Vegetables and Polenta b) Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Bacon Braised Belgian Endive and Pears These two dishes were quite delicious and each meat was perfectly prepared. I would have preferred creamy polenta with my lamb, but it was still quite tasty with the polenta triangles. At first I thought the lamb was somewhat bland, but I realized underneath the lincoln log stack of lamb, were the "tian" of vegetables that reminded me of a grilled ratatouille (thin slices of roasted red pepper, zucchini and eggplant) - bursting with flavor and a perfect match to the lamb. Cheese: We prefer mild cheeses and steered clear of the bleu. I don't remember the exact names of the cheeses we had, but there were at least 15 or 16 to choose from. Dessert: a) Passion Fruit Chiboust, Roasted Banana, Coconut Foam, Macadamia Nuts and Thai Basil b) Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces (One vanilla and one chocolate) My passion fruit chiboust was everything I hoped it would be. The chiboust was a frozen passion fruit custard that was bruleed on top. All of the flavors together were phenomenal. My husband thoroughly enjoyed his ginormous souffle, but I didn't think it was that special. I was stuffed to the gills by the end of the meal and I even had half of my lamb packed to go. Good thing I didn't order 7 courses. Service was impeccable and friendly from the moment you step out of your car at valet parking (which, incidentally, costs $11). Their wine menu is extensive, but the selection is limited if you want to order by the glass or the 1/2 bottle. They have a full bar as well. We were in the dining room the left of the entrance and there was one unisex bathroom on that side. Sharing a bathroom with the male gender, particularly those who don't know how to aim properly, is not high on my list of things I like to do and not on my list of things I should have to experience in a restaurant of this caliber... Case in point, it was disgusting. Fortunately, I notified the staff and they told me they'd have it 'serviced' immediately. I didn't check out the bathroom on the other side of the restaurant, but I will be sure to investigate on a future visit. Aside from the bathroom follies, this was a magnificent meal. The atmosphere is refined, elegant, yet still relaxed, which makes for a lovely meal. For those celebrating a special occasion, they bring out an assortment of mini desserts to enjoy. Every party left the restaurant with a mini-loaf of apricot blueberry breakfast bread. It has been touted as one of the best restaurants in SF and now I see why

I go once a year... Party of 2. We took the three course menu- Starter: Ahi Tuna and Scallops Mains: Venison and Beef Dessert: Souffle and Cheese Bottle of German red wine. Lots of little surprises along the dinner on the house. Everything was perfectly cooked and very tasty. Wonderful service personnel. Steven the manager is the most wonderful person.

This place is so damn good its hard not to give it 5 stars. I would definitely go back. But after all the hype I guess I was expecting to be blown away. Kinda stuffy, and the food was all very good but each dish I would say I've tried better in the city. With one exception. The Foie Gras. It was the best Ive ever had. Without a doubt. Decadent. I also tried the tuna, the snapper and the beef. All were good but just somewhat unmemorable. Definitely would say there are better places to go for steak and fish (and in retrospect that isn't what to order here anyway...) The cheese cart is deservedly famous. Go for the one soaked in Chimay beer. And some goat cheese that was so good I have had to remove it from my memory because it was interfereing with my job performance. Service was very good, almost too good. The sommelier sent two bottles back before we even tried them. Then once she found one that was good, she asked if we wanted to taste the others for comparison. It was actually really helpful. The other thing to note about GD is that it is expensive, yes, but they make you feel like it is worth it and you are getting something special. From free amuse bouche to extra "hole filler" sweets at the end, it is certainly a memorable experience.

When I called to make a reservation, the hostess asked, "Is this for a special occasion?" I said that I was leaving San Francisco. She said, "San Francisco will miss you." They gave me a dessert at the end of the meal which spelled out "Bon Voyage" in chocolate. Gary Danko is a thoughtful place. They really take care of you when you're here. I had this dish that had mango in it, and some other junk like rice and something else. They even had an Indian guy serve it to me! Man, they really think of everything.

Delicious, beautiful, relaxing, amazing service... very pleasant, elegant, and unforgettable experience. The menu changes, but quality is always amazing! If you have some $ to drop, this is a Must Must in SF.

Not only was GD's exceptional and creative, it was one of the most delicious things I've ever eaten anywhere. One of the best dining experiences of my life. I had taken in all the hype and was unsure that it could be matched but I must say that it was one of the most memorable meals of my life. The service was absolutely spectacular from taking my coat when we walked in the door to calling us a taxi at the end of our meal. In between, we feasted and I mean, we ate the point of feeling like complete gluttons...and we enjoyed every minute of our three hour meal. The seared foie gras and lobster risotto appetizers were both perfection. The bison with black pepper gnocchi was so rich but delicious and perfectly prepared. My husband scarfed down his beef tenderloin to rave reviews. The cheese cart was impressive and although we were miserably full by dessert, we managed to get down some bites of the creme brulee trio and Grand Marnier souffle. The sommilier helped us pick a fantastic bold Cabernet from a small production vineyard in Napa...when in Rome. Our service was top notch and the youth of the servers was a nice break from a typical stuffy, formal restaurant. The decor was classy and beautiful with impressive flower arrangements. We had a great table and could not have been more pleased (with the exception of the bill.) It is pricey, but worth it.

This place is warm and inviting. We didn't have reservations so we had to sit at the bar. The nice thing is, they regulate the bar and seat people without reservations at the bar as space opens up. As we were standing in the bar area, a staff member approached us and took our drink order (we didn't have to order a drink over someone eating at the bar). This was the beginning of an evening of exceptional service. All staff members and bartenders were friendly, responsive and knowledgeable. We had the taster with the wine pairing. The presentation excellent, the food was warm and the pairing was interesting and well thought out. The food arrived in a timely manner and we were never rushed. This was nice since our dinner was the only plans we had for the evening. We opened with a corn chowder soup taster from the chef to get the buds salivating and it did the job. It was sweet and full of flavor. The first course was Oysters with Caviar. It was rich and succulent though I would have preferred a smaller portion (but who can complain about that?). The second course was the Horseradish Crusted Salmon Filet. This was simply one of the best pieces of fish I have ever had. If you visit this restaurant and enjoy salmon, do yourself a favor and try this. Third course was Seared Filet of Beef. My wife liked hers buy I found mine just too lost in the sauce and frankly lacking the top notch quality I find at high end steak houses. A great steak needs a grill, salt and pepper. The Cheese course was nice though I found the cheese selection to be rather vanilla, I enjoyed them nevertheless. The desert wasn't overwhelming but a nice way to finish the meal. Overall the experience was excellent which is why I gave it 5 stars. It is expensive but you are paying for exceptional service, very good food and of course, location.

Maybe I'll see him there!

I've tried my share of amazing restaurants here in San Francisco, and I have to say, Gary Danko is amongst the top of my list. First of all, I love how intimate this restaurant is. It doesn't seat more than 60 people with a private dining room of 10 and only 10. I like the whole ambiance and the feel of this chic and romantic restaurant. These were our selections of the night: Sweet Corn Soup with Dungeness Crab, Red Pepper, Creme Fraiche and Ham Biscuit. It doesn't get better than this on a cold night in the city. Lobster Salad with Avocado, Roasted Tomatoes, Haricot Verts and Mustard-Tarragon Vinaigrette. The vinaigrette topped it all off. Seared Scallops with Butternut Squash Puree Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Puree, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Corn and Tarragon Seared Filet of Bef Quail Stuffed with Foie Gras Chocolate Souffle Creme Brulee Everything was a winner in its own way, every time I finish a dish I silently said to myself, "I wish I had one more bite of that!" Yup, it's that good. Do try it. It doesn't get ridiculously expensive like French Laundry and you get what you pay for.

How can I not love this place? My husband proposed here. Cheezy, "romantic" dinner proposal? Yes. But the man knows I love me some fine food, so he hit the nail on the head. =) After a massage at local spa, we head inside and find a chic little place cleanly and sharply decorated. The hostess offers to take our coat, while we wait at the bar to be seated. A suit-clad waiter leads us to our table and walks us through the tasting menu complete with caviar and cheese courses, and wine menu of near bibilical proportions. I find my favorite wine and order a glass. This is no small feat since my favorite is a Christoffel Erben Riesling - 2001 if they've got it. Google this wine, and tell me if you find it. If you do, I'll give you a big wet kiss. =) As we pour over the menu, I'm just taking in everything and savoring the complimentary taster soup they bring. We order our wine and food, and settle in. I had: -Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing -Horseradish Crusted Salmon Medallion with Dilled Cucumbers -Pan Seared Beef Filet with Potato, Leeks, Bacon and Perigord Black Truffles and topped it off with bananas flambe (a special request) prepared tableside. It was DELICIOUS! Kevin had: -Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Winter Root Vegetables and Thyme Oil -Seared Striped Bass with Butternut Squash, Sour Cherries and Thyme -Lemon Herb Duck Breast with Duck Hash and Spice Poached Quince followed by a cheese course and apples flambe. (Side Note: Poor hubby picked a stinky cheese that tasted like B.O. ...oh well, you can't win 'em all, right?) Everything was perfectly prepared, seasoned, and spot on. My salmon was the least favorite, but it was still lovely. Kevin gave me a bit of his duck hash and I almost died it was that good. I also almost ate all of this risotto after devouring my tuna. They could bring me those two dishes all night long and I'd be happy. After the proposal, as if on cue, the waiter steps out with a two flutes of sparkling wine set on a beautiful silver platter. 'Compliments of the house, and a most heartfelt congratulations,' he says. Nice touch. We finish our dessert and are heading out when the waiter brings one last treat. A cute little pineapple breakfast cake to celebrate with the following morning. We've been back a few times since, and it's been delightful everytime. $300 for two people, and it's definitely worth every penny (and really quite reasonable if you think about what you get, and the quality) We'd go weekly if we weren't so far from the city, and oh yea, if we were gazillionaires. =)

Wow, can I just say Gary Danko rocked my world!! This is literally the most best service I have ever had at a restaurant, and I've been to quite a number of fine establishments in Europe and North America. I checked out Gary Danko while on vacation in SF, because of a friend's recommendation. Took the cable car from O'Farrell St, which was a fun roller coaster ride and they dropped us off right by the restaurant. The impeccable service started the moment we entered the restaurant. You could just tell that their waiters are well seasoned and trained to offer such sophisticated service. Coat check cards are unheard of at this place. Their wait staff will remember which pieces you've checked in for you. A free round of drinks was offered, when our table wasn't quite ready upon our arrival. After we were seated, they apologized again, and brought us two rounds of complimentary mini appetizers for starter. Gary Danko's only offer prix fix menus. However, the serving size is quite generous, and remains the same whether you take the 3-course menu or the 5-course menu. Their wine menu did not disappoint, either. My recent addiction is German rieslings, and I was pleased to see a whole section dedicated to German rieslings. For appetizers, we ordered Risotto with Rock Shrimp, and Seared Foie Gras. The risotto was ULTRA delicious with large pieces of shrimps, while the foie gras was rich, and melts in your mouth. Following the appetizers, we then proceeded to Quail Stuffed with Foie Gras, and Filet of Beef. I was surprised that they actually give you TWO quails. Have you ever had an experience where you are toally overdoing yourself, but you simply couldn't stop eating because the food is so good?? Well, I definitely had that problem by the time I got to the second quail (not that I'm complaining). We were then greeted by the cheese tray. They offer a wide selection of fine cheeses, served with crackers and grapes. The best part is they would place your cheese selection on the plate according to how strong it is. Just when we thought the dinner was winding down, our waiter brought us a plate of complimentary finger-sized desserts, which we happily accepted. They also gave us a Gary Danko muffin, on our way out. What really distinguished their service was an episode that happened after we left the restaurant. I noticed that I left my scarf there, after I got back to the hotel around midnight. So I decided to give them a call and see if I could pick it up the next day. Much to my surprise, the manager offered have one of their employees drop off my scarf AT MY HOTEL after work!! When I received it at the front desk next morning, it was placed in a nice Gary Danko back with a beautiful ribbon, another muffin, and two of their house tea bags!!! I can only imagine that they must have their customers' best interests at heart, for their service to reach such a level of sophistication. I would definitely recommend Gary Danko to anyone who wants to celebrate a special occasion with some amazing food, wine and top-of-the-line service.

Decided to switch it up this year for my birthday and came to Gary Danko's w/ a couple friends and boyfriend. Definitely not disappointed, but I'm in agreement w/ other 4 star reviews - not the best meal of my life, which is what I was expecting after running up such a tab. The offerings are definitely hit or miss, not what I was anticipating at such a revered restaurant. My friends and I pulled the ol' switcheroo at every course just so we could sample as much as possible. I'll concentrate on what I had since I can't make a well-informed enough critique on something I only had one spoonful of. (We went w/ 5 courses since we're GD virgins and wanted to go all out). Here's the rundown: Appetizer: Crispy Farm Egg with White Polenta, Royal Trumpet Mushrooms, Frisée and Pancetta - 4/5 for me. Really yummy, nice textures, but overall too salty which seems to be a recurring complaint in this forum. (Of course I wolfed it down regardless). I also had a bite of my friend's foie gras which was heaven on a plate. I'll be getting that next time. Fish and Seafood: Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Corn and Tarragon - 3/5. It was cooked perfectly but the flavors were nothing too memorable for me. I might skip this course next time. Meat and Game Birds: Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Potato-Sorrel Purée, Peas, Bacon, Pickled Jalapeños and Maple Glaze - 5/5. Highlight of my entire meal. The pork belly melts in your mouth with just the right amount of fat to make it flavorful but not overbearing. I was not as impressed with the tenderloin - I would've rather had another portion of the pork belly if I could. The pickled jalapeños seemed odd to me. Cheese: I am no cheese connossieur so I picked the Iberico and went with the suggestions from the waiter. At this point I was too full to really appreciate any of them and didn't get to finish it since I wanted to spare some room for dessert. Definitely skipping this course next time. Dessert: Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces - 4/5? This is probably my all-time favorite dessert so I always order it by default if I see it on the menu, but I can't say that it was any better than any of the other chocolate souffles I've had in my life. It's something you can easily screw up preparing, but difficult to make it stand-outish (if that makes any sense). If I could make one suggestion, I'd opt for the raspberry sauce in place of the vanilla or chocolate sauces that came with it. Overall, pleased w/ the experience (after the initial sticker shock waned). I'll be coming back, but definitely not going for 5 courses again - too much food (especially at 10 o' clock at night) and now I know what to order.

It's been long time over due but this is honestly more then a great restaurant or their great food, its also about their unmatched service and experience I have yet to get from any other restaurant I have ever ate at.

First, service is outstanding at Gary Danko (5 stars). Our host was attentive. Water glass was always full and bread replenished on your side plate. Dishes were well paced. Restaurant is very popular and it gets very loud so it's difficult to have a conversation if you have a soft voice. We chose the 4 Courses for $85 per person. Food was OK (3.5 stars) Salad of Baby Beets, Duck Prosciutto, Lolla Rossa, Goat Cheese Truffles and Hazelnut Vinaigrette --- Very good Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing --- Very good Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Morel Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon --- Disappointed. Must have been an off night for this dish. We each ordered it and the lobster tail was a bit on the tough, chewy side. Lobster claw was tender. Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Potato Ramp Puree, Cauliflower, Fava Beans and Maple Cider Glaze --- Good. Pork belly part was yummy with melt in your mouth fat from the belly. Tenderloin part was a little dry but eating it together with the belly fat improved it. Juniper Crusted Venison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Glazed Cipollini Onions and Herb Spaetzle --- Excellent Lamb loin and lamb sausage (no description online) --- Very good. Lamb was cooked perfectly. Did not care for the flavor of the sausage. Flambéed Cherries with Mascarpone Filled Crépes, Graham Cracker-Pecan Streusel and Vanilla Bean Ice Cream --- Very good Some other details worth mentioniong (5 stars) - - Complimentary birthday dessert was a nice added touch. It was a deliciously light lime / lemon cheesecake. - Complimentary gift for the ladies to take home for the next morning was another nice surprise. - Purse hook for purses provided is another small detail that is appreciated. - Valet parking was a nice convenience - $11 + tip. Torn between awarding 3 or 4 stars but the lobster dish which we were all eager to have ultimately dropped this review to 3 stars.

    10/6/2008

    Gary Danko's cuisine  = ambrosial

    Ambrosial def.
    1. exceptionally pleasing to taste or smell; especially delicious or fragrant  
    2. worthy of the gods; divine

    My eyes were most certainly larger than my stomach and I had a difficult time deciding what to get.  On the left side of the menu, there is a seasonal tasting menu available.  On the right side, you can customize a 3, 4 or 5 (or probably more if you wanted) course menu.  The categories to choose from included appetizers, fish & seafood , meat & poultry, cheese course and dessert.    You could select as many items from each category as you like for your 3 ($66), 4 ($83), or 5 ($98) (or more) courses.  

    At first glance I wanted one salad, one fish, one game and 2 desserts.  I wanted the passion fruit chiboust and the trio of creme brulees.  My husband scolded me for wanting two desserts.  Talk about not watching what I am eating!    Then, the table next to us received their duck dish and lobster dish.  And then the cheeses being served to the table on the other side of us looked so good, too!!  I was already planning on getting the lamb and the lobster, but the duck looked SO good!! So, at this point, I was trying to mentally prepare myself to pig out on a 7-course meal.  

    Then, reality set in.  I can't eat that much even if I wanted to.  Time to reign it in and be realistic here.  In the end we had one 4-course and one 5-course (we ordered the cheese course to share).
    Our selections:

    Salad / Soup -
    a) Thai Lobster Salad with Melons, Pickled Cucumbers and Mango Dressing
    b) Risotto with Lobster, Laughing Bird Shrimp, Corn, Butternut Squash, Parmigiano-Reggiano and Basil Oil

    The husband proclaimed the risotto the best he has ever eaten.  The texture of the risotto was incredible.  I've definitely never had a risotto quite like that. It was fabulous.

    Fish & Seafood -
    a) Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelles, Corn and Tarragon
    b) Branzini with Orzo, Roasted Peppers, Patty Pan Squash, Tomato Confit and Watercress

    The texture of the branzini - light and crunchy on the outside, so moist, light and flaky on the inside ...
    The lobster was delicious and the corn was so sweet.

    Meat & Poultry-
    a) Herb Crusted Loin of Lamb with Tian of Vegetables and Polenta
    b) Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Bacon Braised Belgian Endive and Pears

    These two dishes were quite delicious and each meat was perfectly prepared.  I would have preferred creamy polenta with my lamb, but it was still quite tasty with the polenta triangles.  At first I thought the lamb was somewhat bland, but I realized underneath the lincoln log stack of lamb, were the "tian" of vegetables that reminded me of a grilled ratatouille (thin slices of roasted red pepper, zucchini and eggplant) - bursting with flavor and a perfect match to the lamb.

    Cheese:
    We prefer mild cheeses and steered clear of the bleu.  I don't remember the exact names of the cheeses we had, but there were at least 15 or 16 to choose from.

    Dessert:
    a) Passion Fruit Chiboust, Roasted Banana, Coconut Foam, Macadamia Nuts and Thai Basil
    b) Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces (One vanilla and one chocolate)

    My passion fruit chiboust was everything I hoped it would be.  The chiboust was a frozen passion fruit custard that was bruleed on top.  All of the flavors together were phenomenal.  
    My husband thoroughly enjoyed his ginormous souffle, but I didn't think it was that special.

    I was stuffed to the gills by the end of the meal and I even had half of my lamb packed to go. Good thing I didn't order 7 courses.

    Service was impeccable and friendly from the moment you step out of your car at valet parking (which, incidentally, costs $11).

    Their wine menu is extensive, but the selection is limited if you want to order by the glass or the 1/2 bottle.  They have a full bar as well.

    We were in the dining room the left of the entrance and there was one unisex bathroom on that side.  Sharing a bathroom with the male gender, particularly those who don't know how to aim properly,  is not high on my list of things I like to do and not on my list of things I should have to experience in a restaurant  of this caliber... Case in point, it was disgusting.  Fortunately, I notified the staff and they told me they'd have it 'serviced' immediately.  I didn't check out the bathroom on the other
    side of the restaurant, but I will be sure to investigate on a future visit.

    Aside from the bathroom follies, this was a magnificent meal.  The atmosphere is refined, elegant, yet still relaxed, which makes for a lovely meal.

    For those celebrating a special occasion, they bring out an assortment of mini desserts to enjoy.

    Every party left the restaurant with a mini-loaf of apricot blueberry breakfast bread.

    It has been touted as one of the best restaurants in SF and now I see why

    3/28/2009

    Wow, can I just say Gary Danko rocked my world!!  This is literally the most best service I have ever had at a restaurant, and I've been to quite a number of fine establishments in Europe and North America.

    I checked out Gary Danko while on vacation in SF, because of a friend's recommendation.  Took the cable car from O'Farrell St, which was a fun roller coaster ride and they dropped us off right by the restaurant.

    The impeccable service started the moment we entered the restaurant.   You could just tell that their waiters are well seasoned and trained to offer such sophisticated service. Coat check cards are unheard of at this place.  Their wait staff will remember which pieces you've checked in for you.

    A free round of drinks was offered, when our table wasn't quite ready upon our arrival.  After we were seated,  they apologized again, and brought us two rounds of complimentary mini appetizers for starter.  

    Gary Danko's only offer prix fix menus.  However, the serving size is quite generous, and remains the same whether you take the 3-course menu or the 5-course menu.  Their wine menu did not disappoint, either.  My recent addiction is German rieslings, and I was pleased to see a whole section dedicated to German rieslings.

    For appetizers, we ordered Risotto with Rock Shrimp, and Seared Foie Gras.  The risotto was ULTRA delicious with large pieces of shrimps, while the foie gras was rich, and melts in your mouth.

    Following the appetizers, we then proceeded to Quail Stuffed with Foie Gras, and Filet of Beef.  I was surprised that they actually give you TWO quails.  Have you ever had an experience where you are toally overdoing yourself, but you simply couldn't stop eating because the food is so good??  Well, I definitely had that problem by the time I got to the second quail (not that I'm complaining).

    We were then greeted by the cheese tray.  They offer a wide selection of fine cheeses, served with crackers and grapes.  The best part is they would place your cheese selection on the plate according to how strong it is.

    Just when we thought the dinner was winding down, our waiter brought us a plate of complimentary finger-sized desserts, which we happily accepted.  They also gave us a Gary Danko muffin, on our way out.

    What really distinguished their service was an episode that happened after we left the restaurant.   I noticed that I left my scarf there, after I got back to the hotel around midnight.  So I decided to give them a call and see if I could pick it up the next day.  Much to my surprise, the manager offered have one of their employees drop off my scarf AT MY HOTEL after work!!  When I received it at the front desk next morning, it was placed in a nice Gary Danko back with a beautiful ribbon, another muffin, and two of their house tea bags!!!  I can only imagine that they must have their customers' best interests at heart, for their service to reach such a level of sophistication.

    I would definitely recommend Gary Danko to anyone who wants to celebrate a special occasion with some amazing food, wine and top-of-the-line service.

    Decided to switch it up this year for my birthday and came to Gary Danko's w/ a couple friends and boyfriend.  Definitely not disappointed, but I'm in agreement w/ other 4 star reviews - not the best meal of my life, which is what I was expecting after running up such a tab.  The offerings are definitely hit or miss, not what I was anticipating at such a revered restaurant.  My friends and I pulled the ol' switcheroo at every course just so we could sample as much as possible.  I'll concentrate on what I had since I can't make a well-informed enough critique on something I only had one spoonful of.  (We went w/ 5 courses since we're GD virgins and wanted to go all out).  Here's the rundown:

    Appetizer:  Crispy Farm Egg with White Polenta, Royal Trumpet Mushrooms, Frisée and Pancetta - 4/5 for me. Really yummy, nice textures, but overall too salty which seems to be a recurring complaint in this forum.  (Of course I wolfed it down regardless).  I also had a bite of my friend's foie gras which was heaven on a plate.  I'll be getting that next time.

    Fish and Seafood:  Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Corn and Tarragon - 3/5.  It was cooked perfectly but the flavors were nothing too memorable for me.  I might skip this course next time.

    Meat and Game Birds:  Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Potato-Sorrel Purée, Peas, Bacon, Pickled Jalapeños and Maple Glaze - 5/5.  Highlight of my entire meal.  The pork belly melts in your mouth with just the right amount of fat to make it flavorful but not overbearing.  I was not as impressed with the tenderloin - I would've rather had another portion of the pork belly if I could.  The pickled jalapeños seemed odd to me.

    Cheese:  I am no cheese connossieur so I picked the Iberico and went with the suggestions from the waiter.  At this point I was too full to really appreciate any of them and didn't get to finish it since I wanted to spare some room for dessert.  Definitely skipping this course next time.

    Dessert:  Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces - 4/5? This is probably my all-time favorite dessert so I always order it by default if I see it on the menu, but I can't say that it was any better than any of the other chocolate souffles I've had in my life.  It's something you can easily screw up preparing, but difficult to make it stand-outish (if that makes any sense).  If I could make one suggestion, I'd opt for the raspberry sauce in place of the vanilla or chocolate sauces that came with it.

    Overall, pleased w/ the experience (after the initial sticker shock waned).  I'll be coming back, but definitely not going for 5 courses again - too much food (especially at 10 o' clock at night) and now I know what to order.
